---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const principles = [
  ["Kubernetes-native, not Kubernetes-adjacent", "Runs are CRDs. Jobs are Jobs. Workspaces are PVCs. Paddock adds vocabulary to Kubernetes; it does not hide Kubernetes."],
  ["Harness-agnostic", "If it runs in a container and accepts a prompt, it works. No harness gets privileged treatment in the core."],
  ["Separation of concerns", "The run platform, the bridges, and the broker are three independent components with a clean contract. Each is swappable. Each is independently operable."],
  ["Secure by default", "No long-lived credentials in agent containers. Default-deny egress. Per-run branch namespaces. Policy-gated repo access."],
  ["Template once, run many", "The same harness template backs a Linear delegation, a CLI invocation, a nightly cron, and a GitHub webhook. One catalog, many entry points."],
  ["Observable by construction", "Every run emits structured progress events. Every egress attempt is logged. Every credential issuance is audited."],
  ["The unit of work terminates", "Runs are batch jobs. They start, do a thing, and exit. Continuity across runs comes from shared state outside the run, not from keeping processes alive."],
];

const notList = [
  ["Not an agent framework", "Paddock doesn't define how agents think, reason, or use tools. That lives in the harness."],
  ["Not a model provider", "Paddock does not host, route, or fine-tune models. It just lets you point harnesses at whichever provider you're using."],
  ["Not a workflow engine", "Paddock runs individual agent invocations. If you need DAGs or fan-out/fan-in, use Argo Workflows and have each step submit a HarnessRun."],
  ["Not an IDE", "Interactive, long-lived, human-in-the-loop sessions are a different product. Paddock is for headless, delegated work."],
  ["Not a replacement for your CI", "Paddock agents can open PRs; your CI decides whether those PRs are mergeable. That separation is load-bearing."],
];
---
<BaseLayout title="About" pathname="/about">
  <article class="container" style="padding-block: var(--space-8);">
    <header class="prose">
      <h1>About Paddock</h1>
    </header>

    <section class="prose">
      <h2>What Paddock is</h2>
      <p>
        Paddock is an open-source, Kubernetes-native platform for running headless
        AI agent harnesses — Claude Code, Codex CLI, OpenCode, Pi, or anything
        else you can put in a container — as templated, sandboxed, observable
        batch workloads.
      </p>
      <p>
        You define a harness once. You invoke it many times, from many entry
        points, against many repos, under policy. Kubernetes schedules the work,
        persists the workspace, streams progress back, and enforces the security
        boundary.
      </p>
      <p>
        The shortest description: <em>the plumbing that makes agentic work a
        first-class citizen of your cluster, with the credential handling and
        egress control you'd want before letting an LLM anywhere near
        production code.</em>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="prose">
      <h2>Why it exists</h2>
      <p>
        Teams are wiring up coding agents as CronJobs, Argo Workflows, or
        bespoke Python scripts to handle bug triage, backlog grooming, code
        migrations, and incident response. Every team rebuilds the same four
        things:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>A way to template harnesses so they can be reused across tasks.</li>
        <li>A way to persist and share workspaces across runs, so the agent doesn't start cold every time.</li>
        <li>A way to integrate with their issue tracker or chat tool, so humans can delegate.</li>
        <li>A way to stop the agent from exfiltrating secrets, pushing to <code>main</code>, or installing arbitrary things from the internet.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>Paddock is that shared substrate.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Core principles</h2>
      <p class="prose">These are the tiebreakers when design decisions get contested.</p>
      <ul class="principles">
        {principles.map(([title, body]) => (
          <li>
            <strong>{title}.</strong> {body}
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What Paddock deliberately is not</h2>
      <ul class="principles">
        {notList.map(([title, body]) => (
          <li>
            <strong>{title}.</strong> {body}
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="prose">
      <h2>The north star, in one sentence</h2>
      <blockquote>
        Paddock lets a platform team publish a catalog of safe, templated AI
        harnesses that anyone — or any system — in their organization can invoke
        to get real work done, with the credentials, networks, and repos those
        runs touch governed by policy the security team actually wrote.
      </blockquote>
    </section>
  </article>

  <style>
    .principles {
      list-style: none;
      padding: 0;
      margin: var(--space-4) 0 var(--space-5);
      display: grid;
      gap: var(--space-4);
      max-width: var(--prose-max-w);
    }
    .principles li {
      padding-left: var(--space-4);
      border-left: 2px solid var(--color-accent);
    }
    blockquote {
      margin: var(--space-5) 0;
      padding: var(--space-5);
      background: var(--color-bg-2);
      border-radius: var(--radius-md);
      font-style: italic;
      color: var(--color-text);
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
